      {
        "id": 284408,
        "name": "",
        "username": "Herohtar",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/herohtar/{size}/43780_2.png",
        "created_at": "2026-02-13T05:58:53.371Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"tdbe1\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"67199\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/tdbe1/48/55943_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> tdbe1:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I don’t consider it normal for my image gallery app to be full of folders generated by random separate apps.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Regardless of whether you consider it normal, it most certainly is. <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/os/Environment#DIRECTORY_PICTURES\"><code>Environment.DIRECTORY_PICTURES</code></a> (the “Pictures” folder) is the standard shared directory for apps to save images for the user to access. I just checked my phone and “Pictures” has 11 folders from other apps in it in <em>addition</em> to Signal.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"tdbe1\" data-post=\"5\" data-topic=\"67199\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/tdbe1/48/55943_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> tdbe1:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I’ve developed apps up to android 11, and I’ve never ran into issues with doing this.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Filesystem permissions in Android have changed a lot since then.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"tdbe1\" data-post=\"5\" data-topic=\"67199\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/tdbe1/48/55943_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> tdbe1:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>My Signal already has Media Storage Permission granted.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>This is the “Photos and videos” <em>read</em> permission. Signal doesn’t request <em>write</em> permission to anything; it uses the shared folders that it already has access to (Pictures, Movies, etc).</p>",
